# Release <area-domain>-context

You are shepherding a maintainer through the full release ritual for the `<area-domain>-context` contextualizer. This is the canonical guided path; `RELEASING.md` (or your equivalent manual checklist) is the human-readable fallback. Follow the phases below in order. Halt on any error.

> **Note to Adopters:** This template is domain-agnostic. Replace placeholders before committing the rendered command to your repo's `.claude/commands/release.md`:
> * `<area-domain>` - your domain stem (e.g. 'identity', 'inventory')
> * `<area-domain>-context` - your skill/CLI/plugin name
> * `<your-git-host>` - your git host (e.g., "github.com", "ghe.your-org.com")
> * `<host-cli>` - your host CLI (`gh` for GitHub/GHE, `glab` for GitLab)
> * `<HOST_ENV>` - the env var your host CLI uses to target a specific instance (e.g., `GH_HOST` for GHE; remove if you only target one host)

## For new maintainers (read this first)

* **Who this is for:** anyone maintaining this repo. The release slash command exists so you don't need tribal knowledge from prior maintainers to ship a release.
* **Prereqs:**
  * `<host-cli>` authed to your git host with repo scope - verify with `<host-cli> auth status`. If not authed: `<host-cli> auth login --hostname <your-git-host>`.
  * `jq` and `zip` installed (standard on macOS; `apt install jq zip` or equivalent on Linux).
  * Clean working tree on the branch you want to release from (usually `main`).
* **Time budget:** 10 min for a patch (content refresh), 20 min for a minor (new features), longer for a major (breaking changes - double-check the upgrade story in README).
* **Escape hatch:** if anything fails partway through, fall back to your manual `RELEASING.md` checklist. Nothing this command does is irreversible before the host-release step (Phase 9).

## Argument parsing

The user invoked with `$ARGUMENTS`. Parse as follows:

* **Empty** -> ask interactively: "Which bump? major, minor, patch, or an explicit X.Y.Z version?"
* **major, minor, patch** -> read current version from `bin/<area-domain>-context` and compute the next. Show the diff (e.g., 1.0.0 -> 1.1.0), pause for confirmation.
* **X.Y.Z** matching `^[0-9]+\.[0-9]+\.[0-9]+$` -> use literal. Still show current -> new and confirm.
* **X.Y.Z "release notes text"** -> literal version; use the second arg as the starting draft for release notes.
* **Anything else** -> reject, fall back to interactive.

Store the resolved version as `NEW_VERSION` for use in all subsequent phases.

## Phase 1 - Preflight

Run these checks in order. Halt with remediation guidance on any failure.

1. **Tools present:**
   ```bash
   command -v <host-cli> && command -v jq && command -v zip
   ```
   If any missing: stop and tell the maintainer which to install.

2. **Host CLI authed:**
   ```bash
   <HOST_ENV>=<your-git-host> <host-cli> auth status
   ```
   Must show "Logged in to <your-git-host>". If not: `<host-cli> auth login --hostname <your-git-host>`.

3. **Working tree clean:**
   ```bash
   git status --porcelain
   ```
   Must return empty. If dirty, itemize the changes and ask the maintainer to commit or stash first.

4. **Branch check:**
   ```bash
   git rev-parse --abbrev-ref HEAD
   ```
   Report the current branch. If it is not `main`, require explicit confirmation: "You're on branch <branch>, not main. Continue anyway?"

5. **Validator passes:**
   ```bash
   ./verify.sh
   ```
   Must finish with 'Failed: 0'. If any check fails, halt and show the failing check name(s).

## Phase 2 - Version resolution

Read the current version:
```bash
CURRENT=$(grep -m1 '^VERSION=' bin/<area-domain>-context | sed 's/VERSION="//' | sed 's/"//')
```

Compute `NEW_VERSION` per the arg parsing above. Display:
* **Current:** `X.Y.Z` -> **New:** `A.B.C`

Pause for confirmation. On no/abort, stop cleanly.

## Phase 3 - Bump the version surfaces

Edit each file; show a diff summary after each edit. `.claude-plugin/plugin.json` is the one version surface every contextualizer carries; the `# Version:` / `VERSION=` lines in `bin/<area-domain>-context` — and the test suite's version assertion — belong to the optional CLI pattern this release flow assumes (see the 4-place version sync section in `skill-engine/docs/04-delivery.md#4-place-version-sync`). This Phase bumps the three file-resident surfaces below; a fixture-harness enhancement will add a `verify.sh` version-consistency check, so until then run Phase 5 and eyeball the Phase 6 diff to catch drift.

1. **`bin/<area-domain>-context`** (two places):
   * Header comment: `# Version: X.Y.Z` -> `# Version: <NEW_VERSION>`
   * `VERSION="X.Y.Z"` -> `VERSION="<NEW_VERSION>"`
2. **`.claude-plugin/plugin.json`** version field:
   ```bash
   jq --arg v "$NEW_VERSION" '.version = $v' .claude-plugin/plugin.json > /tmp/plugin.json.tmp
   mv /tmp/plugin.json.tmp .claude-plugin/plugin.json
   ```

## Phase 4 - Draft the CHANGELOG entry

1. **Collect changes since the last tag:**
   ```bash
   LAST_TAG=$(git describe --tags --abbrev=0 2>/dev/null || echo "")
   if [ -n "$LAST_TAG" ]; then
     git log "$LAST_TAG"..HEAD --oneline
   else
     git log HEAD --oneline | head -30
   fi
   ```
2. **Draft an entry in your `CHANGELOG.md` format.** Move any `[Unreleased]` bullets under the new `[<NEW_VERSION>] - YYYY-MM-DD` header; add new bullets for release-only changes. Use the fixed type set:
   * `<type>: <concise description> (<affected files/area>)`
   Types: `add`, `fix`, `change`, `remove`, `deprecate`.
3. **Pause.** Show the draft and invite the maintainer to edit inline before Phase 5. Especially for minor/major releases, a human pass on the CHANGELOG is worth it.

## Phase 5 - Re-run the validator

```bash
./verify.sh
```
Must pass with `Failed: 0`. Halt on any failure; show the failing check name(s) for triage. (Version-surface consistency is a planned fixture-harness check; for now, eyeball-review the diff in Phase 6 to catch missed bumps.)

## Phase 6 - Commit (destructive gate #1)

```bash
git add bin/<area-domain>-context .claude-plugin/plugin.json CHANGELOG.md
git commit -m "chore(release): v<NEW_VERSION>"
```
Show the commit with `git show --stat HEAD`. Pause before pushing - last chance to amend.

## Phase 7 - Push

```bash
git push origin <current-branch>
```
Capture the branch name from Phase 1.4 above.

## Phase 8 - Build the Desktop zip (two names)

```bash
bin/<area-domain>-context package
# produces <area-domain>-context-v<NEW_VERSION>.zip

cp "<area-domain>-context-v<NEW_VERSION>.zip" "<area-domain>-context.zip"
# stable-named copy for /releases/latest/download/ URL
```
Verify both files exist and their sizes match. The versioned zip is the canonical release artifact; the stable-named copy exists so `https://<your-git-host>/<your-org>/<repo>/releases/latest/download/<area-domain>-context.zip` always resolves to the current release without per-release URL churn.

## Phase 9 - Create the host release (destructive gate #2)

1. **Draft release notes** from the CHANGELOG entry added in Phase 4. Write to a temp file:
   ```bash
   cat > /tmp/release-notes-$NEW_VERSION.md <<'EOF'
   <paste the CHANGELOG entry body here - everything under the version heading, up to the next entry or the EOF>
   EOF
   ```
   **Pause:** let the maintainer edit this draft. They may want to add upgrade notes, known issues, or acknowledgments.

2. **Create the release:** creates the tag, pushes it, creates the release page, and uploads both zip assets in one call:
   ```bash
   <HOST_ENV>=<your-git-host> <host-cli> release create "v$NEW_VERSION" \
     "./<area-domain>-context-v$NEW_VERSION.zip" \
     "./<area-domain>-context.zip" \
     --title "v$NEW_VERSION" \
     --notes-file "/tmp/release-notes-$NEW_VERSION.md"
   ```

3. **Clean up** the temp file and the stable named local copy: `rm /tmp/release-notes-$NEW_VERSION.md <area-domain>-context.zip`

## Phase 10 - Verify and report

1. **Confirm the release:**
   ```bash
   <HOST_ENV>=<your-git-host> <host-cli> release view "v$NEW_VERSION"
   ```
   Show the output. Confirm both zip assets are listed.

2. **Print the release URL:** `https://<your-git-host>/<your-org>/<repo>/releases/tag/v$NEW_VERSION`

3. **Next steps for the maintainer:**
   * **Plugin marketplace sync:** If your plugin-marketplace lives in a separate repo (the common case at most orgs), the new `plugin.json` version does NOT auto-propagate. You must copy the updated artifacts into the marketplace repo and bump its `plugin.json`. See `skill-engine/docs/04-delivery.md`.
   * **Org-wide skill provisioning:** (optional) If your org provisions skills centrally (e.g., via Anthropic's Organization settings > Skills), notify the admin with the new zip so they can re-upload for all users. Skip if not applicable.
   * **Paranoid final check:** `./verify.sh` one more time on a fresh clone to catch anything local-env specific.

## Failure modes and recovery

* **Phase 1 preflight fails:** fix the underlying issue (install tool, authenticate, clean working tree) and re-run.
* **Phase 5 validator fails after version bump:** if a check fails, halt and show the failing check name(s). Fix the file, re-run `./verify.sh`; once green, continue with Phase 6. (A future fixture-harness enhancement will add a version-consistency check; until then, eyeball-review the diff in Phase 6.)
* **Phase 9 release create fails:** common causes are (a) tag already exists (someone else created vX.Y.Z already - delete with `<host-cli> release delete` or pick a new version), or (b) auth scope too narrow (re-run `<host-cli> auth refresh -h <your-git-host> -s repo`).
* **Bad release shipped:** see your `RELEASING.md` > "Rollback" - delete the release (or mark as pre-release), upload the previous good zip, cut a patch release with the fix.

## Guardrails

* **Never skip Phase 5** (post-bump validator). Until a future fixture-harness enhancement adds a version-consistency check to `verify.sh`, the Phase 6 diff review is the only line of defense against shipping a mismatched `plugin.json`.
* **Never commit `--no-verify`** in this flow. If a hook fails, investigate.
* **Never force-push** the release branch.
* **Pause before pushing** (Phase 6-7) and before creating the host release (Phase 9). Those are the two points of no return for this session.

## Notes for adopters

* The two destructive gate pauses (commit/push, then host release) are deliberate. Do not collapse them into a single "ship it" button - the source pattern's value is the human review that happens at each gate.
* Tag the source-of-truth docs from this command (CHANGELOG conventions, version-sync, marketplace sync) rather than restating them. The release flow is the runner; the docs are the *spec*. Drift between the two is the most common failure mode for a guided ritual; minimize it.